              <h2>Loan payment formula (amortization formula)</h2>
              <p>
                For a fixed-rate installment loan with regular payments
                (monthly, quarterly, etc.), the standard loan payment formula
                is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  \( P = \dfrac{r \times L}{1 - (1 + r)^{-n}} \)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm mt-2">where:</p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li>
                    <strong>P</strong> = payment per period (what you pay each
                    month, quarter, etc.)
                  </li>
                  <li><strong>L</strong> = loan amount (principal)</li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>r</strong> = interest rate per period (annual rate ÷
                    payments per year)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    <strong>n</strong> = total number of payments (years ×
                    payments per year)
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>Special case: zero interest</h3>
              <p>
                If the interest rate is 0, the formula above would divide by
                zero. In that case, the payment is simply:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">\( P = \dfrac{L}{n} \)</p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use this loan payment formula calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Solve for the payment</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>loan amount</strong> (principal you are
                  borrowing).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>annual interest rate</strong> (nominal rate,
                  e.g., 6 for 6%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>loan term</strong> in years and choose how
                  often you pay (monthly, bi-weekly, etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally, add an
                  <strong>extra payment per period</strong> to see how it
                  accelerates payoff.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>Calculate payment</strong> to see:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Payment per period based on the formula</li>
                    <li>Total of payments and total interest</li>
                    <li>Full amortization schedule</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>2. Solve for the loan amount (inverse formula)</h3>
              <p>
                Sometimes you know how much you can afford to pay each month and
                want to know how large a loan that supports. Rearranging the
                formula gives:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  \( L = P \times \dfrac{1 - (1 + r)^{-n}}{r} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>Solve for Loan Amount</strong> tab to enter your
                target payment, interest rate, and term. The calculator will
                compute the maximum principal \( L \) that fits those
                constraints.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you borrow <strong>$25,000</strong> at
                <strong>6% annual interest</strong>, to be repaid monthly over
                <strong>5 years</strong>.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Convert the annual rate to a monthly rate:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      \( r = \dfrac{0.06}{12} = 0.005 \) per month
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute the total number of payments:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      \( n = 5 \times 12 = 60 \) payments
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply the loan payment formula:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      \( P = \dfrac{0.005 \times 25000}{1 - (1 + 0.005)^{-60}}
                      \approx 483.32 \)
                    </p>
                  </div>
                  <p>You would pay about <strong>$483.32 per month</strong>.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute total interest:
                  <div class="formula-box">
                    <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                      Total paid = \( 483.32 \times 60 \approx 28{,}999.20 \)<br />
                      Total interest = 28,999.20 − 25,000 =
                      <strong>3,999.20</strong>
                    </p>
                  </div>
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Deriving the loan payment formula (intuition)</h2>
              <p>
                A fixed-rate loan is the mirror image of an annuity: instead of
                depositing equal payments and watching the balance grow, you
                borrow a lump sum and make equal payments that shrink the
                balance to zero.
              </p>
              <p>
                The present value of an annuity with payment \( P \), rate \( r
                \), and \( n \) periods is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-mono text-sm">
                  \( PV = P \times \dfrac{1 - (1 + r)^{-n}}{r} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For a loan, the present value \( PV \) is the loan amount \( L
                \). Solving this equation for \( P \) gives the standard loan
                payment formula used in this calculator.
              </p>

              <h2>Common pitfalls when using the loan payment formula</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mixing annual and monthly rates:</strong> Always
                  convert the annual rate to a per-period rate before using the
                  formula.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Using years instead of number of payments:</strong>
                  Multiply years by payments per year to get \( n \).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ignoring fees and changing rates:</strong> The formula
                  assumes a constant interest rate and equal payments. Fees and
                  variable rates require more advanced models.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rounding too early:</strong> Keep full precision in
                  intermediate steps; round only the final payment for better
                  accuracy.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>
                Can I use this for mortgages, auto loans, and personal loans?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. As long as the loan has a
                <strong>fixed interest rate</strong> and
                <strong>equal periodic payments</strong>, the same loan payment
                formula applies. Mortgages, car loans, and most personal loans
                fit this pattern.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my loan compounds daily but I pay monthly?</h3>
              <p>
                In that case, the true math is slightly more complex. A common
                approximation is to convert the daily rate to an effective
                monthly rate and use that as \( r \). For most consumer loans,
                the difference is small, but for large balances or long terms
                you may want a more detailed model.
              </p>

              <h3>How do extra payments affect the formula?</h3>
              <p>
                The core formula still determines the
                <strong>required</strong> payment. Any extra amount you pay is
                treated as an additional principal reduction, which shortens the
                loan term and reduces total interest. Our calculator simulates
                this month by month in the amortization table.
              </p>
